Week 1

I used Google to figure out how to load the tidyverse library. Specifically “How to add a code chunk that loads the tidy verse library”.From there, I made sure to to use different credible websites to ensure that I find the correct code. The first website I opened was Stack Overflow (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58289197/how-to-write-an-r-chunk-to-load-the-tidyverse).

However, I noticed that the comments were asking the user to clarify his question (i.e R Setup, or R Notebook, R Markdown). From this I employed another search clarifying that I am using R Notebook. From there I looked at another Stack Overflow forum (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58568048/tidy-verse-issue) and I also looked at the Tidyverse documentation (https://tidyverse.tidyverse.org/) on how to use the library.

To check that it was working, I ran the code and compared my Console output to the Tidyverse documentation output (https://tidyverse.tidyverse.org/). To double check, I also saved the file and looked at the .nbhtml version. I was able to get a condensed summary of conflicts with other packages

ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
head(MFIndD_REI_read)
  1. The column type of “response” is a character type and the column type for “scored_response” is a numeric (dbl). They are different because chr is assigned when a column contains mixed data types. For example, some values are numeric and some are strings. This classifies as chr. On the other hand, “scored_response” is classified as dbl bc the values are numeric values.
MFIndD_REI_read <- MFIndD_REI_read %>%

    response == "Strongly Disagree" ~ 1,
    response == "Strongly Agree" ~ 5,
    TRUE ~ as.double(response)
    
  ))

There are 4 distinct values in the “condition” column.

distinct_condition_values <- c("dots_EqSizeSep","dots_EqSizeRand","blob_shifted","blob_stacked")
print(distinct_condition_values)
[1] "dots_EqSizeSep"  "dots_EqSizeRand" "blob_shifted"    "blob_stacked"

Pseudocode/Plan/Logic: 1. Vector with distinction condition values: Distinct_condition_values 2. Initialize an empty vector for mean reaction time. This is so that when the loop iterates, it stores the value in this vector. **Learned that I need to set it to the length of distinct_condition_values to avoid any other values 3. Loop a. iterate over each index of distinct_condition_value b. store the mean reaction time for the current condition at i. This makes sure that the mean is in the write place in the new vector. c. select and filter the rows where the condition from the intial table matches with distinct_condition_value d. now that the conditions matched, we can now look at corresponding rt e. Take the mean from the rt e. store in the vector mean_reaction_times

for (i in seq_along(distinct_condition_values)) {
  mean_reaction_times[i] <- mean(MFIndD_probtask_read$rt[MFIndD_probtask_read$condition == distinct_condition_values[i]])
}
print (mean_reaction_times)
[1] 889.8202 879.6184 892.2855 847.5153

When I ran this I got “[1] 889.8202 879.6184 892.2855 847.5153 NaN NaN NaN NaN”. When I first initialized mean_reaction_time, I had c() so I can store the values in here. But I realized I had to set it equal to the length of the vector of the distinct columns so there are no other values. I also added the numeric().

accuracy_table_mean_across <- MFIndD_probtask_read %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%
  summarize(
    across(c(rt, correct), mean, na.rm = TRUE)
  )

print(accuracy_table_mean_across)
accuracy_table_mean <- MFIndD_probtask_read %>%
  group_by(condition) %>%

    mean_rt = mean(rt, na.rm = TRUE),
    accuracy = mean(correct, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
